First, we express \(\sin 3x\) as \(3 \sin x - 4 \sin^3 x\) and \(\sin 2x\) as \(2 \sin x \cos x\). Substituting these into the equation, we get: \[ a \cdot (\sin x + 2 \sin x \cos x) = 3 \sin x - 4 \sin^3 x \] Factoring out \(\sin x\) on both sides, we have: \[ a \cdot \sin x (1 + 2 \cos x) = \sin x (3 - 4 \sin^2 x) \] Assuming \(\sin x \neq 0\) (which is valid in the interval \((0, \pi)\)), we divide both sides by \(\sin x\): \[ a (1 + 2 \cos x) = 3 - 4 \sin^2 x \] Using the identity \(\sin^2 x = 1 - \cos^2 x\), we rewrite the right-hand side: \[ a (1 + 2 \cos x) = 3 - 4 (1 - \cos^2 x) = -1 + 4 \cos^2 x \] Factoring the right-hand side, we get: \[ a (1 + 2 \cos x) = (2 \cos x - 1)(2 \cos x + 1) \] Since \(2 \cos x + 1 \neq 0\) (as \(\cos x \neq -1/2\) in \((0, \pi)\)), we can cancel \(2 \cos x + 1\) from both sides: \[ a = 2 \cos x - 1 \] This equation shows that \(a\) is a function of \(\cos x\). The function \(2 \cos x - 1\) is continuous and strictly decreasing from 1 to -3 as \(x\) ranges from 0 to \(\pi\). However, we must consider the point \(x = 2\pi/3\) where \(\cos x = -1/2\). At this point, the original equation simplifies to \(0 = 0\), which is always true for any \(a\). Therefore, \(x = 2\pi/3\) is always a solution. To determine when there are more than one solution, we analyze the function \(a = 2 \cos x - 1\). This function is strictly decreasing from 1 to -3, except at \(x = 2\pi/3\) where it has a removable discontinuity with limit -2. Thus, for \(a \in (-3, 1)\), the equation \(a = 2 \cos x - 1\) has exactly one solution. However, when \(a = -2\), the solution \(x = 2\pi/3\) is already counted, leading to only one solution. Therefore, the set of \(a\) with more than one solution is \((-3, 1)\) excluding \(-2\), which can be written as \((-3, -2) \cup (-2, 1)\).
